<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Where to Place the Heat Mat</h2>

  <p>
    The heat mat should sit directly under the tray so that warmth moves evenly upward through the soil.
  </p>

  <p>
    Avoid placing trays partially on the mat or offset from it, as this can lead to uneven germination and growth.
  </p>

  <p>
    A clean, full contact setup usually works best.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When to Use (and Stop Using) the Heat Mat</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Use it:</strong> during germination and early seedling growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduce or remove it:</strong> once seedlings are established.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Peppers benefit most from warmth early on. After that, strong light and balanced conditions matter more.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When a Thermostat Is Worth It</h2>

  <p>
    In a cool basement, a thermostat can help keep soil temperature consistent, especially if the room runs colder than expected or fluctuates slightly.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is not always required, but it becomes more useful as conditions become less predictable or colder overall.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/when-a-thermostat-matters-for-seed-starting-heat-mats/">when a thermostat matters for seed-starting heat mats</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Using Heat Mats for Everything</h3>
  <p>
    Not all crops need bottom heat. Peppers benefit the most, so they should drive the setup.
  </p>

  <h3>Leaving Heat Mats On Too Long</h3>
  <p>
    Once seedlings are established, excess warmth is less helpful than strong lighting.
  </p>

  <h3>Uneven Tray Placement</h3>
  <p>
    Partial coverage leads to inconsistent germination and growth.
  </p>

  <h3>Trying to Over-Control Temperature</h3>
  <p>
    A simple, steady setup usually works better than constant adjustment.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Heat Mats Fit Into the Full Setup</h2>

  <p>
    A heat mat improves germination, but it works best alongside proper light placement, airflow, and watering practices.
  </p>

  <p>
    In a basement setup, these factors all interact. Improving one part of the system often improves the others as well.
  </p>

